name: Sunnyside Conservatory
description: Built in 1898, this gem is an extraordinary gathering space and botanic jewel, set off by a hundred-year old palm grove and the dramatic foliage of its surrounding gardens.

name: Green Stairs
description: Stunning views of downtown SF and the TransAmerican Pyramid from this stairwell! Those running or moving quickly on these stairs beware, Signs of wear and tear on the stairs have made some of the steps slightly trickier to navigate so caution is advised.

name: Francisco Street Steps
description: Connecting the waterfront to the North Beach neighborhood, this stairway is an urban adventure. The entrance is hidden between apartment buildings at 150 and 155 Francisco St., off Sansome Street. Walk through a courtyard to make your start. Midway, take a left on Grant St. half a block to Jack Early Park, which offers a short staircase to a lookout that has stunning views of the Bay.

name: Greenwich Street Stairs
description: This popular stairwell maintains an air of mystery and intrigue about it due to the thick  foliage surrounding it. There are two main sections of this stairwell. The upper section of the stairs is made of brick and runs hrough the edge of Pioneer Park. Further down, the stairs pass  underneath several houses before a sharp descent towards Sansome and Greenwich Streets.

name: Filbert Steps
description: What a workout! Hundreds of stairs, great views, gorgeous flowers and trees.

name: Baker Street steps
description: This quiet, residential stretchis the longest continuous staircase in the north side neighborhoods, 202 steps in all. A beautiful view of the Palace of Fine Arts is in store.

name: Vallejo Stairway
description: Want beautiful vistas? Come here! The stairs are surrounded by beautiful, well-maintained gardens. There are three separate stairways that run next to each other.

name: Noe Court Playground
description: This quant neighborhood park is completely gated so smaller kids have free reign. Featuring a playground, grass, picnic area, tennis and basketball courts and a dog-run.

name: Seward Street Slides
description: This unique concrete slide in the Castro is a true gem. Fun for kids and kids at heart.

name: Douglass Playground and Dog Park
description: Douglass Playground has an excellent hillside location complete with trees and rock outcroppings. Highlights include a Clubhouse, children's play area, informal lawn areas, tennis courts, and a baseball field. There are picnic tables, restrooms, and a dog park.

name: Corona Heights Park
description: Offering 360 degree views of San Francisco, this park is great for kids, dogs and urban hikers.

name: Hamilton Recreation Center
description: This community recreation center boasts indoor and outdoor basketball courts, tennis courts, baseball fields, a pool and playgrounds for kids. This stunning new swimming facility features a large, heated pool and two indoor water slides.
open_hours: Monday and Sunday: ClosedTuesday: 9am to 9pmWednesday: 9am to 9pmThursday: 9am to 9pmFriday: 9am to 9pmSaturday: 9am to 5pm
open_days: Monday and Sunday: ClosedTuesday: 9am to 9pmWednesday: 9am to 9pmThursday: 9am to 9pmFriday: 9am to 9pmSaturday: 9am to 5pm

name: Cottage Row
description: Cottage Row is a charming walkway comprised of Victorians cottages of historic significance. Most of the homes were built by William Hollis during the late 1860‰Û_s and 1870‰Û_s.There is also a mini park on Cottage Row.
dogs_notes: A short walk from Japantown and the Fillmore District, the park was recently improved with a new dog play area, retaining wall and plant beds

name: The Little Giants Ballpark
description: Little Giants Park is a 50-by-50-foot replica of AT&T Park designed for little children. It includes an infield, bases, outfield and ballpark iconography that gives tomorrow's Giants the feeling that they are big leaguers playing in a real Major League ballpark.

name: Mission Bay Commons
address: Terry Francois Blvd. and stretches west to Third Street between Mission Bay Boulevards North and South
description: Mission Bay Commons is the newest section of the Mission Bay Park System. Two parcels of this linear park are currently available for public use. The park begins at Terry Francois Blvd. and stretches west to Third Street between Mission Bay Boulevards North and South. Expansive turf spaces surrounded by beautiful plants and trees may be enjoyed from benches and concrete steps. Great for picnics, dogs, biking, exercise and kids.
seating_notes: There are picnic tables available at the Mission Creek Park Sports Courts between 401 and 451 Berry Street underneath the freeway overpass.
restrooms_notes: Public restrooms are available from 8 am to 6 pm at the Pavilion Building located at 290 Channel Street. Public restrooms are also available at 451 Berry Street from 8am to 7:30pm.
dogs_notes: Pets are welcome; however they must be on a leash at all times.The fenced in dog play area is located at the west end of Berry Street before 7th Street. The dog play area is open from 6 am - 10 pm.
notes: Mission Bay Commons is the newest section of the Mission Bay Park System.

name: Alice Street Community Garden
description: This small urban garden is lovingly maintained by seniors and disabled youth from the area. Individual plots of land are located beneath a hand-painted mural. Visitors are welcome to use the space for picnics during daylight hours.
open_notes: Visitors are welcome to use the space for picnics during daylight hours.

name: Presidio Pet Cemetary
description: Dating to the 1950s, this pet cemetary boasts the final resting place for beloved companions like Happy the tiger fish (loved by Kate), Bali the toy poodle (who belonged to Ltc. Boring) and Oreo (the best hamster ever).

name: 16th Avenue Steps
description: 163 tiled mosaic steps are a fantastic find at 16th and Moraga in the Sunset District. Artists Aileen Barr and Colette Crutcher led the project with over 300 locals to create this stunning work of art. The mosaic features a lovely collage of natural creatures and is a joy to observe from a distance and as one climbs the steps leading towards Turtle Hill.

name: Mount Sutro Open Space Reserve
description: This often unnoticed natural site in the city, sits right behind UCSF and is home to the largest Eucalyptus forest in San Francisco. Equipped with a wonderful range of hiking and biking trails, this is a great spot for nature lovers and for those who want to just get away from the hustle and bustle of the city for a while. Those who reach the summit of this mountain will find great spots to enjoy an afternoon picnic. Nature enthusiasts can find rare native plant and animal species all along the trails of Mount Sutro.
restrooms_notes: Public restroom located at the Aldea Center
views_notes: Views can be spotted along the trails and sometimes at the summit

name: Turtle Hill/ Grand View Hill
description: Trek up to the top of this small, but steep hill in the Sunset District  on a clear day and you'll find a breathtaking view of this great city. Three separate routes will lead you to the top of this hill, each with at least 100 steps that may leave you trying to catch your breath when you reach the top. A few seating areas can be found for one to rest and soak in the view, or enjoy a nice picnic. The hill is covered with the original sand from when the area used to be a belt of sand dunes that led to the sea, so be prepared to empty your shoes out.

name: 1331 9th Avenue Parklet
description: This cozy, wood adorned parklet is situated in the heart of the Inner Sunset, right across from one of the best bakeries in the city -- Arizmendi. It is the perfect spot to sit and relax with a nice meal or beverage from the local vendors and to watch locals interact with one another.

name: General Store backyard
description: This lovely backyard is set up for visitors to convene and enjoy a little coastal air. It is behind through General Store, a local artisanal furniture, clothing, tools, plants, household items and books store.
art_notes: Store has art exhibitions and sells local art

name: Outerlands
description: This large parklet has plenty of benches and landscaping.

name: MOJO
description: Parklet designed by Riyad Ghannam of rg-architecture.

name: Four Barrel Coffee
description: Designed by Boor Bridges Architecture

name: FreeWheel Bike Shop
description: Parklet designed by Kanbayashi Designs; plant design by Thrive Lanscaping. Parklet hosted by Freewheel Bike Shop.

name: Blue Fig
description: Parklet designed by Riyad Ghannam of rg-architecture.

name: Revolution Cafe
description: Parklet designed by REBAR.
food_notes: Revolution Cafe, Excape from NY Pizza, Lolo

name: The Crepe House
description: Designed by Riyad Ghannam of rg-architecture.

name: Luna Rienne Gallery
description: Parklet hosted by Luna Rienne Gallery. This artsy parklet is an outdoor installation that changes a few times a year.

name: 150 California St
description: This view terrace is located six stories above the street level. There is a large sculpture, long periods of sunlight, and several types of seating. There are extensive views of the surrounding area.
seating_notes: 40 chairs w/ 10 tables, Linear Seating: only 10'' deep, but approx 82 linear seats

name: Federal Building Sky Garden
description: Designed by Pritzker Prize winner Thom Mayne of Morphosis, this 60-foot-wide terrace on the 11th floor has stunning views to the north and south.
open_notes: To visit the San Francisco Federal Building you will need to show an American ID or international passport. A convenient self-guided tour is available from 9am to 3pm Monday through Friday. Only ‰ÛÏpublic space‰Û can be seen. Elevators and Skygarden accessible by taking elevator to the 12th floor.

name: Crocker Galleria
description: Plenty of benches and lots of lovely trees, shrubs and flowers to offer some respite from the surrounding concrete jungle.
food_notes: Food available inside Crocker Galleria Mall Food Court

name: Rincon Center
description: This large plaza space is found in the interior courtyard between Rincon Center 1 and Rincon Center 2. It features several art sculptures and different types of seating.
seating_notes: 78 on benches and chairs. Also, the cafe provides some of its own seating.

name: Westfield Sky Terrace (Wesfield Center Mall)
description: This extensive 9th floor rooftop space looks onto the dome of the mall and has views westward and sunlight. It does not have direct food service, but food may be found in the food court below in the mall.
food_notes: None, but food on the premises

name: Millenium Tower Plaza
description: This atrium features extensive artwork and is served by a bar/restaurant on the premises. It has various types of seating with tables, and high windows overhead.

name: Marriott Courtyard - C
description: This space features extensive landscaping with several art attractions. Comfortable seating arrangements are located throughout the space. Food service nearby inside the hotel.

name: Marriott Courtyard - A (Starbucks)
description: Thayer referenced something that is not part of the open space requirement, this is pedestrian improvement requirement. Per Thayer: This open space has benches and landscaping along the sidewalk on Folsom at street level.
seating_notes: It appears that one bench near the entrance on 2nd Street is meant to meet this requirement. Per Thayer: 12 linear seats by bench.

name: Intercontinental Hotel_Pacific Terrace
description: The Intercontinental Hotel provides two POPOS on the fourth and sixth floors. They have various seating arrangements and landscaping, each with views of the City.
seating_notes: Unknown - seating arranged for private event(s)
restrooms_notes: Hotel. Could use the lobby restrooms etc

name: Intercontinental Hotel_Bay Terrace
description: The Intercontinental Hotel provides two POPOS on the fourth and sixth floors. They have various seating arrangements and landscaping, each with views of the City.
restrooms_notes: Hotel. Could use the lobby restrooms

name: Gap Building
description: This is a large plaza with several seating areas. Art sculptures are featured along with diverse landscaping.

name: Commercial Street
description: This tree-lined street features seating for your enjoyment and relaxation. Many cafes and restaurants reside along Commercial Street, making it the perfect place to come to for a sit-down meal. Additional outdoor seating is provided during lunch hours. Open at all times.

name: 77 Van Ness Ave
description: This space is in the front lobby of 77 Van Ness. It has tables and chairs and features a sculpture.
reject_reason: Bland lobby with some metal tables and chairs and a sculpture placed as an afterthought. Security guard is friendly but not welcoming of visitors. According to him, the city has not yet officially designated this as a POPOS. It is unknown if it is not quite "ready." Given that it's a sucky space and far away from other spaces, not worth visiting right now.

name: 345 California Center
description: Two POPOS can be found on the west and east sides of the building, both connected by an interior walkway. The East side features a row of benches and some planters. This shady area is a sheltered alcove, great for meeting someone before heading to another destination, or just to use as a shortcut to the other side of the block. The West side can be entered from Sansome Street, next to the Mandarin Hotel. This shady area features a few granite benches and planters with tall bamboo.
seating_notes: Bench for ~3 people; 10 chairs w/ tables

name: 120 Howard St
description: This space features plants along the entirety of the snippet and is served by an espresso cart.

name: 1 Kearny St
description: This rooftop terrace has extensive views of Market St. as well as rooftop architecture of nearby buildings. Landscaping and bench seating support this space.

name: 1 Bush Street
description: This Urban Garden provides a sunken space featuring a water fountain. Space is accessed with stairs from Bush Street and curved walkways from Market street.

name: Marathon Plaza
description: Large, triangular urban garden facing Second Street with a water feature, ample seating, and lush landscaping. Deli and restaurant open to the park provide food and additional seating.

name: 101 2nd St
description: This expansive five-story greenhouse features large trees, an abundance of natural light, and plenty of art. There are two balcony spaces with designer tables and chairs that overlook the enclosed open space. A cafe sits on the property and there is sometimes entertainment at noon for visitors to enjoy.
seating_notes: 25 linear seats on bench/ ledge. 23 tables, 69 chairs

name: 555 Mission St
description: This large plaza has several art and landscaping features. It is located in front of 555 Mission Streets and runs along the west side of the building. There are several distinct sitting areas with different styles of seating.

name: 560 Mission St
description: This beautiful urban garden is accessible from both Mission and Jessie Streets. A tall bamboo grove transforms the surrounding concrete jungle to a more tranquil setting. Grass-coveredTerraced platforms, all at sitting height, step down toward a granite plaza filled with seating. Two cafes sit on the premise, making this a perfect lunch time spot. A shallow pool with a large kinetic sculpture adds to the allurement of the space.
seating_notes: 45 chairs with 15 tables.134 linear seating onl ledges. 10 linear seats on benches

name: 199 Fremont St
description: This large plaza space features extensive rock landscaping and artwork, designed in collaboration by Paul Kos, a conceptual sculptor, and Robert Haas, a poet and landscape architect. There are two adjoined areas, one of which has food service. The plaza is lined with birch trees, Sierra granite, and boulders at sitting height. The garden wall is engraved with a Haas poem and a fountain trickles in to a circular basin adding tranquility to the space.
seating_notes: Rock planter box seating. Approx 114 linear seats plus 17 iondividual rocks

name: Spear Street Plaza
description: Well landscaped walkway with seating and tables.

name: 1 Market St
description: This large plaza is marked by the hexagonal tower that faces the Mission Street entrance. Several food services open to the premises. This is a great spot to stop of a meal or sit down and soak up some sun.

name: 123 Mission St
description: This shady plaza is the perfect spot to escape the congestion of the downtown area. It is subdivided in to three alcoves by densely filled planters, all built at sitting height. The lush green setting softens the concrete and granite surroundings. Four food vendors are located nearby.

name: 14 Fremont St
description: This wide open space is a walkway connecting Fremont Street and 1st Street.  Half of the space is designated for customer seating for the adjacent cafes, while the other half is a cleanly manicured urban garden with patches of landscaped grass and strategically placed planters with trees.

name: 425 Market St
description: This shady urban garden is a great gem tucked between two highrises. Its sleek design features granite seating, flowers, planters, and trees. This is a great spot for relaxing with a good book, or sipping your favorite beverage. Open at all times.

name: 525 Market St
description: This two tiered, urban garden has a granite fountain and plenty of seating. Landscaping softens the hard granite setting and areas offer great patches of sun. A restaurant is located on site and opens in to the space. Open at all times.

name: Citygroup Center
description: Built in the shell of the 1912 neoclassical London-Paris Bank building, this greenhouse provides a more sheltered space, while still letting in plenty of natural light. With its marble arches and corinthian columns, this POPOS is reminiscent of a Roman setting. Palm trees and other plants give a natural repreive to the otherwise cold setting, and an Art Deco bronze sculputer adds an artistic flair to the space. A cafe sits on the premise with plenty of tables and chairs.

name: 100 Pine St
description: Tucked between two skyscrapers, this hidden urban garden is a wonderful little gem that can be accessed either through the front entrance of the building or a narrow walkway on Front Street. This shaded space offers water fountains, beautiful landscaping, and art. Food is offered on the site and there are designer tables and chairs to sit and eat.

name: 101 California St
description: Three large stepped pyramids used for seating and planter beds occupy the perimeter of this expansive plaza. A granite fountain gives the surroundings a peaceful quality. There are two restaurants on the buildings ground floor with ample outdoor seating. This is a great place to stop for lunch and catch some sun.
seating_notes: None. Stairs? Some planter box seating but doesn't meet linear seating specs (12'' H and 9'' depth"

name: One California St
description: Located directly across the street from 50 California, this mini plaza feels like an extension to its neighbor across the way. This snippet also features various shaped planters placed on a striped pavement of green stone and rose-colored granite. The cafe on the ground floor of the building fills some of the space with tables and chairs for its customers. Open at all times.
reject_reason: Outdoor planters. Nice seating and sidewalk space but ultimately not interesting, considering its proximity to other quality POPOS.

name: 50 California St
description: Occupying the building setback, this small plaza and wrap-around walkway is a lovely little spot to stop and sit. It is scattered with various shaped planters, each with ledges placed at sitting height. A small cafe with outdoor seating sits to the side of the space. Open at all times.

name: 343 Sansome St
description: This fifteenth floor open space has excellent views of surrounding buildings and streets, as well as the San Francisco Bay. The open terrace includes various types of seating, beautiful olive trees, and Joan Brown's Four Seasons obelisk which stands in the center. Adjacent to the building, just off Leidesdorff Street, sits a lunchtime mall which is available from 11am to 2pm. Two food vendors are on the ground floor of the building.
seating_notes: 18 chairs, 50 linear seats on planter box sizes.

name: Redwood Park
description: Located at the base of the Transamerica Pyramid, this hidden oasis features a beautiful redwood grove, luscious ferns, and a tall water fountain, making the perfect escape from the bustling surroundings. The area also has an array of bronze sculptures, grassy patches, and ample seating. Take-out food vendors are nearby. This urban park is closed after office hours.
